===
Lord Ashburton Cupid's Victim

One of the most startling announcements came on April 29 of the engagement of Miss Frances Belmont to Lord Ashburton, a descendant of that Lord Ashburton who, as British ambassador at Washington, negotiated the Ashburton treaty. Lord Ashburton, whom Miss Belmont is to marry, Is a widower. His wife, a daughter of Viscount Hood, died a year ago last January. He Is the head of the famous London banking company of Baring.
The career of Miss Belmont reads like a fairy tale. She Is a New Yorker, though she was born In Ireland. Her first appearance on the stage was as one of the broom and mop girls In the chorus of &quot; Miladi.&quot;
&quot; When Maggie Dolan scrubbed the floor
You can bet the floor was clean.&quot;
Miss Belmont scrubbed as she sang In the chorus of twelve girls and she made such a hit that she soon had a chance to make an easier living by posing for art and fashion magazines. She found that there was more money and less work In allowing herself to be photographed than In the life of a chorus girl and she followed this for a little while until she, one day, reappeared on the stage in the Florodora sextet. At this time she was ambitious and asked for something better than the part of a &quot; Pretty Maiden.&quot; This did not fall In with the Idea of her managers, and she left &quot; Florodora.&quot;

Determination Wins High Place.

Her next work was In the &quot;Toreador.&quot; She had a vaulting ambition, and in her Ideas of what part she would like to play, that of the leading woman In &quot;A Message from Mars &quot; took complete possession of her mind. One night Charles Hawtrey was In a box at the &quot; Toreador.&quot;
&quot; Do you see that man over there?&quot; whispered Miss Belmont to the chorus girl next to her. &quot; That's Charles Hawtrey, the great English actor. I am going to get that man to give me a place In his company. You watch and see.&quot;

The next thing that happened was that the world of chorus girls, soubrettes, and managers was electrified to hear that Frances Belmont was engaged as the lending woman of Charles Hawtrey In &quot; A Message from Mars.&quot; How she met Mr. Hawtrey no one could learn. When asked as to how she got the engagement she answered;
&quot; O, he just offered me the part and I accepted it.&quot;
&quot; Had he ever seen you act?&quot;
&quot; O, yes, I went down to a rehearsal and ran through a few roles for him one afternoon and he offered me the contract.&quot;
Managers and every one who had seen Miss Belmont
joined In the prediction that she would not &quot; make good.&quot;
&quot; She has had no experience,&quot; said a well known manager.
&quot; She can't even walk across the stage. I have a dozen girls In my chorus who could do as well as she can.&quot;
That this was all a matter of mere pique was seen when It resulted that Miss Belmont did make good. Now she has made good matrimonially also. Her home is in a little flat In New York with her mother and two sisters. They have even now gone across to be present at the wedding. Miss Belmont herself, however, who feels that her education has been deficient, is In a convent In Paris learning many things which will help to fit her for the high position which she will be called upon to fill.

